page_title #= "Core IO"
page_description #= "Console output and input polling helpers in Beanstalk."
page_head #= theme_head

#[navbar]
#[title, center: CORE IO]

#[section, $md:
    `io` is the prelude namespace alias for `@core/io`.
    Console helpers write string content to the backend output surface.

    [codeblock, $code("bst"):
        io.print("loading...")
        io.line("Hello")
        io.debug("debug details")
        io.warn("warning")
        io.error("error")

        name = "Beanstalk"
        io.line([: Hello, [name]])
    ]

    Strings and templates are accepted at the output boundary. Other values are rejected directly;
    use template interpolation when you want a debug-style message.

    [codeblock, $code("bst"):
        count = 3
        io.line([: count = [count]])
    ]

    Importing `@core/io` explicitly binds the same `io` namespace. Aliasing creates a file-local
    namespace name:

    [codeblock, $code("bst"):
        import @core/io as output

        output.line("Hello from an alias")
    ]

    Input polling lives under `io.input.*`. The handle type `io.input.Input` is opaque: pass it to
    the input functions, but do not construct it with struct syntax or inspect fields.

    [codeblock, $code("bst"):
        input ~= io.input.new()!

        io.input.update(~input)

        if io.input.key_pressed(input, "d"):
            io.line("pressed d")
        ;

        if io.input.pointer_down(input, "left"):
            x = io.input.pointer_x(input)
            y = io.input.pointer_y(input)

            io.line([: pointer [x], [y]])
        ;

        last_key = io.input.last_key_pressed(input)

        if last_key is |key|:
            io.line([: last key: [key]])
        ;

        io.input.close(~input)
    ]

    `io.input.new()` is fallible because backend input support can be unavailable. `update` and
    `close` require mutable access. Polling reads use shared access.

    Keyboard helpers track held, pressed, released, and last-edge states. Single alphabetic key
    strings normalize to lowercase, space is `"Space"`, and special keys use logical names such as
    `"ArrowLeft"`, `"Enter"`, `"Escape"`, `"Backspace"`, and `"Shift"`. Pointer helpers use
    `"left"`, `"middle"`, and `"right"` buttons, plus `Float` pointer coordinates.

    HTML-JS maps console helpers to the browser console and input helpers to window/document-level
    keyboard and pointer polling. HTML-Wasm rejects reachable Core IO calls before lowering until
    it has equivalent support. Browser input events are delivered by the host event loop, so a
    synchronous infinite Beanstalk loop can block new input from being observed.

    Deferred IO surfaces include filesystem/path IO, fetch/network IO, timers, sleep, intervals,
    frame/tick APIs, targeted DOM/canvas input sources, physical key-code APIs, typed key/button
    choices, text entry and IME/composition, touch gestures, gamepads, drag/drop, clipboard, wheel
    scrolling, file picker APIs, full ordered event queues, pressed/released collections, relative
    or DPI-scaled pointer coordinates, configurable default suppression, and non-JS lowerings.
]
